# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genome-wide-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In genomics, a **genome-wide association study** (**GWA study**, or **GWAS**), is an observational study of a genome-wide set of genetic variants in different individuals to see if any variant is associated with a trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA studies typically focus on associations between single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) and traits like major human diseases, but can equally be applied to any other genetic variants and any other organisms.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] When applied to human data, GWA studies compare the DNA of participants having varying phenotypes for a particular trait or disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] These participants may be people with a disease (cases) and similar people without the disease (controls), or they may be people with different phenotypes for a particular trait, for example blood pressure.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This approach is known as phenotype-first, in which the participants are classified first by their clinical manifestation(s), as opposed to genotype-first.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Each person gives a sample of DNA, from which millions of genetic variants are read using SNP arrays.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] If there is significant statistical evidence that one type of the variant (one allele) is more frequent in people with the disease, the variant is said to be *associated* with the disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The associated SNPs are then considered to mark a region of the human genome that may influence the risk of disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA studies investigate the entire genome, in contrast to methods that specifically test a small number of pre-specified genetic regions.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Hence, GWAS is a *non-candidate-driven* approach, in contrast to *gene-specific candidate-driven studies*.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA studies identify SNPs and other variants in DNA associated with a disease, but they cannot on their own specify which genes are causal.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The first successful GWAS published in 2002 studied myocardial infarction.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This study design was then implemented in the landmark GWA 2005 study investigating patients with age-related macular degeneration, and found two SNPs with significantly altered allele frequency compared to healthy controls.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] As of 2017, over 3,000 human GWA studies have examined over 1,800 diseases and traits, and thousands of SNP associations have been found.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Except in the case of rare genetic diseases, these associations are very weak, but while each individual association may not explain much of the risk, they provide insight into critical genes and pathways and can be important when considered in aggregate.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Any two human genomes differ in millions of different ways.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] There are small variations in the individual nucleotides of the genomes (SNPs) as well as many larger variations, such as deletions, insertions and copy number variations.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Any of these may cause alterations in an individual's traits, or phenotype, which can be anything from disease risk to physical properties such as height.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Around the year 2000, prior to the introduction of GWA studies, the primary method of investigation was through inheritance studies of genetic linkage in families.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This approach had proven highly useful towards single gene disorders.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] However, for common and complex diseases the results of genetic linkage studies proved hard to reproduce.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] A suggested alternative to linkage studies was the genetic association study.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This study type asks if the allele of a genetic variant is found more often than expected in individuals with the phenotype of interest (e.g. with the disease being studied).
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Early calculations on statistical power indicated that this approach could be better than linkage studies at detecting weak genetic effects.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In addition to the conceptual framework several additional factors enabled the GWA studies.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] One was the advent of biobanks, which are repositories of human genetic material that greatly reduced the cost and difficulty of collecting sufficient numbers of biological specimens for study.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Another was the International HapMap Project, which, from 2003 identified a majority of the common SNPs interrogated in a GWA study.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The haploblock structure identified by HapMap project also allowed the focus on the subset of SNPs that would describe most of the variation.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Also the development of the methods to genotype all these SNPs using genotyping arrays was an important prerequisite.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The most common approach of GWA studies is the case-control setup, which compares two large groups of individuals, one healthy control group and one case group affected by a disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] All individuals in each group are typically genotyped at common known SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The exact number of SNPs depends on the genotyping technology, but are typically one million or more.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] For each of these SNPs it is then investigated if the allele frequency is significantly altered between the case and the control group.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In such setups, the fundamental unit for reporting effect sizes is the odds ratio.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The odds ratio is the ratio of two odds, which in the context of GWA studies are the odds of case for individuals having a specific allele and the odds of case for individuals who do not have that same allele.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] When the allele frequency in the case group is much higher than in the control group, the odds ratio is higher than 1, and vice versa for lower allele frequency.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Additionally, a P-value for the significance of the odds ratio is typically calculated using a simple chi-squared test.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Finding odds ratios that are significantly different from 1 is the objective of the GWA study because this shows that a SNP is associated with disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Because so many variants are tested, it is standard practice to require the p-value to be lower than 5×10−8 to consider a variant significant.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] A key step in the majority of GWA studies is the imputation of genotypes at SNPs not on the genotype chip used in the study.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This process greatly increases the number of SNPs that can be tested for association, increases the power of the study, and facilitates meta-analysis of GWAS across distinct cohorts.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Genotype imputation is carried out by statistical methods that impute genotypic data to a set of reference panel of haplotypes, which typically have been densely genotyped using whole-genome sequencing.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] These methods take advantage of sharing of haplotypes between individuals over short stretches of sequence to impute alleles.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Existing software packages for genotype imputation include IMPUTE2, Minimac, Beagle and MaCH.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In addition to the calculation of association, it is common to take into account any variables that could potentially confound the results.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Sex, age, and ancestry are common examples of confounding variables.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Moreover, it is also known that many genetic variations are associated with the geographical and historical populations in which the mutations first arose.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Because of this association, studies must take account of the geographic and ethnic background of participants by controlling for what is called population stratification.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] If they did not do so, the studies could produce false positive results.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] After odds ratios and P-values have been calculated for all SNPs, a common approach is to create a Manhattan plot.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In the context of GWA studies, this plot shows the negative logarithm of the P-value as a function of genomic location.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Thus the SNPs with the most significant association stand out on the plot, usually as stacks of points because of haploblock structure.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Importantly, the P-value threshold for significance is corrected for multiple testing issues.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The exact threshold varies by study, but the conventional genome-wide significance threshold is 5×10−8 to be significant in the face of hundreds of thousands to millions of tested SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA studies typically perform the first analysis in a discovery cohort, followed by validation of the most significant SNPs in an independent validation cohort.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Attempts have been made at creating comprehensive catalogues of SNPs that have been identified from GWA studies.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] As of 2009, SNPs associated with diseases are numbered in the thousands.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The first GWA study, conducted in 2005, compared 96 patients with **age-related macular degeneration** (ARMD) with 50 healthy controls.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] It identified two SNPs with significantly altered allele frequency between the two groups.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] These SNPs were located in the gene encoding complement factor H, which was an unexpected finding in the research of ARMD.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The findings from these first GWA studies have subsequently prompted further functional research towards therapeutical manipulation of the complement system in ARMD.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Another landmark publication in the history of GWA studies was the **Wellcome Trust Case Control Consortium** (WTCCC) study, the largest GWA study ever conducted at the time of its publication in 2007.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The WTCCC included 14,000 cases of seven common diseases (~2,000 individuals for each of coronary heart disease, type 1 diabetes, type 2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis, Crohn's disease, bipolar disorder, and hypertension) and 3,000 shared controls.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This study was successful in uncovering many genes associated with these diseases.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Since these first landmark GWA studies, there have been two general trends.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] One has been towards larger and larger sample sizes.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In 2018, several genome-wide association studies are reaching a total sample size of over 1 million participants, including 1.1 million in a genome-wide study of educational attainment follow by another in 2022 with 3 million individuals and a study of insomnia containing 1.3 million individuals.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The reason is the drive towards reliably detecting risk-SNPs that have smaller effect sizes and lower allele frequency.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Another trend has been towards the use of more narrowly defined phenotypes, such as blood lipids, proinsulin or similar biomarkers.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] These are called *intermediate phenotypes*, and their analyses may be of value to functional research into biomarkers.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] A variation of GWAS uses participants that are first-degree *relatives* of people with a disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This type of study has been named **genome-wide association study by proxy** (*GWAX*).
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] A central point of debate on GWA studies has been that most of the SNP variations found by GWA studies are associated with only a small increased risk of the disease, and have only a small predictive value.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The median odds ratio is 1.33 per risk-SNP, with only a few showing odds ratios above 3.0.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] These magnitudes are considered small because they do not explain much of the heritable variation.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This heritable variation is estimated from heritability studies based on monozygotic twins.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] For example, it is known that 40% of variance in depression can be explained by hereditary differences, but GWA studies only account for a minority of this variance.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Several studies have looked into the use of risk-SNP markers as a means of directly improving the accuracy of prognosis.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Some have found that the accuracy of prognosis improves, while others report only minor benefits from this use.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Generally, a problem with this direct approach is the small magnitudes of the effects observed.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] A small effect ultimately translates into a poor separation of cases and controls and thus only a small improvement of prognosis accuracy.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] An alternative application is therefore the potential for GWA studies to elucidate pathophysiology.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] One such success is related to identifying the genetic variant associated with response to anti-hepatitis C virus treatment.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] For genotype 1 hepatitis C treated with Pegylated interferon-alpha-2a or Pegylated interferon-alpha-2b combined with ribavirin, a GWA study has shown that SNPs near the human IL28B gene, encoding interferon lambda 3, are associated with significant differences in response to the treatment.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] A later report demonstrated that the same genetic variants are also associated with the natural clearance of the genotype 1 hepatitis C virus.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] These major findings facilitated the development of personalized medicine and allowed physicians to customize medical decisions based on the patient's genotype.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The goal of elucidating pathophysiology has also led to increased interest in the association between risk-SNPs and the gene expression of nearby genes, the so-called expression quantitative trait loci (eQTL) studies.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The reason is that GWAS studies identify risk-SNPs, but not risk-genes, and specification of genes is one step closer towards actionable drug targets.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] As a result, major GWA studies by 2011 typically included extensive eQTL analysis.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] One of the strongest eQTL effects observed for a GWA-identified risk SNP is the SORT1 locus.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Functional follow up studies of this locus using small interfering RNA and gene knock-out mice have shed light on the metabolism of low-density lipoproteins, which have important clinical implications for cardiovascular disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] For example, a meta-analysis accomplished in 2018 revealed the discovery of 70 new loci associated with atrial fibrillation.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] It has been identified different variants associated with transcription factor coding-genes, such as TBX3 and TBX5, NKX2-5 o PITX2, which are involved in cardiac conduction regulation, in ionic channel modulation and cardiac development.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] It was also identified new genes involved in tachycardia (CASQ2) or associated with alteration of cardiac muscle cell communication (PKP2).
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Research using a High-Precision Protein Interaction Prediction (HiPPIP) computational model that discovered 504 new protein-protein interactions (PPIs) associated with genes linked to schizophrenia.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] One study indicates that GWAS is substantially more effective for identifying genes associated with schizophrenia (and highly polygenic phenotypes in general) than candidate-driven studies.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Another group of researchers conducted a joint analysis of GWAS summary statistics from seventeen pain susceptibility traits in the UK Biobank and revealed 99 genome-wide significant risk loci, among which 34 loci were new.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Also, with leave-one-trait-out meta-analyses these loci were grouped in four categories: Loci associated with nearly all pain-related traits, associated with a single trait, associated with multiple forms of skeletomuscular pain and with headache-related pain.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Moreover, 664 genes were mapped to the 99 loci by genomic proximity, eQTLs and chromatin interaction, where 15% of these genes showed differential expression in individuals with acute or chronic pain compared to healthy individuals.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Population level GWA studies may be used to identify adaptive genes to help evaluate ability of species to adapt to changing environmental conditions as the global climate becomes warmer.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This could help determine extirpation risk for species and could therefore be an important tool for conservation planning.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Utilizing GWA studies to determine adaptive genes could help elucidate the relationship between neutral and adaptive genetic diversity.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA studies act as an important tool in plant breeding.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] With large genotyping and phenotyping data, GWAS are powerful in analyzing complex inheritance modes of traits that are important yield components such as number of grains per spike, weight of each grain and plant structure.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In a study on GWAS in spring wheat, GWAS have revealed a strong correlation of grain production with booting data, biomass and number of grains per spike.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA study is also a success in study genetic architecture of complex traits in rice.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The emergences of plant pathogens have posed serious threats to plant health and biodiversity.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Under this consideration, identification of wild types that have the natural resistance to certain pathogens could be of vital importance.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Furthermore, we need to predict which alleles are associated with the resistance.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA studies is a powerful tool to detect the relationships of certain variants and the resistance to the plant pathogen, which is beneficial for developing new pathogen-resisted cultivars.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The first GWA study in chickens was done by Abasht and Lamont in 2007.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This GWA was used to study the fatness trait in F2 population found previously.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Significantly related SNPs were found are on 10 chromosomes (1, 2, 3, 4, 7, 8, 10, 12, 15 and 27).
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] GWA studies have several issues and limitations that can be taken care of through proper quality control and study setup.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Lack of well defined case and control groups, insufficient sample size, control for population stratification are common problems.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] On the statistical issue of multiple testing, it has been noted that "the GWA approach can be problematic because the massive number of statistical tests performed presents an unprecedented potential for false-positive results".
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This is why all modern GWAS use a very low p-value threshold.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] In addition to easily correctible problems such as these, some more subtle but important issues have surfaced.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] A high-profile GWA study that investigated individuals with very long life spans to identify SNPs associated with longevity is an example of this.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The publication came under scrutiny because of a discrepancy between the type of genotyping array in the case and control group, which caused several SNPs to be falsely highlighted as associated with longevity.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] The study was subsequently retracted, but a modified manuscript was later published.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Now, many GWAS control for genotyping array.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] If there are substantial differences between groups on the type of genotyping array, as with any confounder, GWA studies could result in a false positive.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Another consequence is that such studies are unable to detect the contribution of very rare mutations not included in the array or able to be imputed.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Additionally, GWA studies identify candidate risk variants for the population from which their analysis is performed, and with most GWA studies historically stemming from European databases, there is a lack of translation of the identified risk variants to other non-European populations.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] For instance, GWA studies for diseases like Alzheimer's disease have been conducted primarily in Caucasian populations, which does not give adequate insight in other ethnic populations, including African Americans or East Asians.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Alternative strategies suggested involve linkage analysis.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] More recently, the rapidly decreasing price of complete genome sequencing have also provided a realistic alternative to genotyping array-based GWA studies.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] High-throughput sequencing does have potential to side-step some of the shortcomings of non-sequencing GWA.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Cross-trait assortative mating can inflate estimates of genetic phenotype similarity.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Genome-wide association studies may also be challenged in their examination of behavioral traits by population-specific environmental and cultural factors, which might affect gene expression.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] This means that results obtained in different populations might not be readily generalized to other populations in the examination of behavioral traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Genotyping arrays designed for GWAS rely on linkage disequilibrium to provide coverage of the entire genome by genotyping a subset of variants.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Because of this, the reported associated variants are unlikely to be the actual causal variants.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Associated regions can contain hundreds of variants spanning large regions and encompassing many different genes, making the biological interpretation of GWAS loci more difficult.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Fine-mapping is a process to refine these lists of associated variants to a credible set most likely to include the causal variant.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Fine-mapping requires all variants in the associated region to have been genotyped or imputed (dense coverage), very stringent quality control resulting in high-quality genotypes, and large sample sizes sufficient in separating out highly correlated signals.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] There are several different methods to perform fine-mapping, and all methods produce a posterior probability that a variant in that locus is causal.
[src:genome-wide-association/genome-wide-association-study] Because the requirements are often difficult to satisfy, there are still limited examples of these methods being more generally applied.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] A **haplotype** (haploid genotype) is a group of alleles in an organism that are inherited together from a single parent.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Many organisms contain genetic material (DNA) which is inherited from two parents.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Normally these organisms have their DNA organized in two sets of pairwise similar chromosomes.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The offspring gets one chromosome in each pair from each parent.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] A set of pairs of chromosomes is called diploid and a set of only one half of each pair is called haploid.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The haploid genotype (haplotype) is a genotype that considers the singular chromosomes rather than the pairs of chromosomes.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] It can be all the chromosomes from one of the parents or a minor part of a chromosome, for example a sequence of 9000 base pairs or a small set of alleles.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Specific contiguous parts of the chromosome are likely to be inherited together and not be split by chromosomal crossover, a phenomenon called genetic linkage.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] As a result, identifying these statistical associations and a few alleles of a specific haplotype sequence can facilitate identifying *all other such* polymorphic sites that are nearby on the chromosome (imputation).
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Such information is critical for investigating the genetics of common diseases; which have been investigated in humans by the International HapMap Project.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Other parts of the genome are almost always haploid and do not undergo crossover: for example, human mitochondrial DNA is passed down through the maternal line, and the Y chromosome is passed down the paternal line.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] In these cases, the entire sequence can be grouped into a simple evolutionary tree, with each branch founded by a unique-event polymorphism mutation (often, but not always, a single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP)).
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Each clade under a branch, containing haplotypes with a single shared ancestor, is called a haplogroup.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] An organism's genotype may not define its haplotype uniquely.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] For example, consider a diploid organism and two bi-allelic loci (such as SNPs) on the same chromosome.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Assume the first locus has alleles *A* or *T* and the second locus *G* or *C*.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Both loci, then, have three possible genotypes: (*AA*, *AT*, and *TT*) and (*GG*, *GC*, and *CC*), respectively.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] For a given individual, there are nine possible configurations (haplotypes) at these two loci (shown in the Punnett square below).
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] For individuals heterozygous at both loci, the gametic phase is ambiguous - in these cases, an observer does not know which haplotype the individual has, e.g., TA vs AT.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The only unequivocal method of resolving phase ambiguity is by sequencing.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] However, it is possible to estimate the probability of a particular haplotype when phase is ambiguous using a sample of individuals.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Given the genotypes for a number of individuals, the haplotypes can be inferred by haplotype resolution or haplotype phasing techniques.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] These methods work by applying the observation that certain haplotypes are common in certain genomic regions.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Therefore, given a set of possible haplotype resolutions, these methods choose those that use fewer different haplotypes overall.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The specifics of these methods vary - some are based on combinatorial approaches (e.g., parsimony), whereas others use likelihood functions based on different models and assumptions such as the Hardy–Weinberg principle, the coalescent theory model, or perfect phylogeny.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The parameters in these models are then estimated using algorithms such as the expectation-maximization algorithm (EM), Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), or hidden Markov models (HMM).
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Microfluidic whole genome haplotyping is a technique for the physical separation of individual chromosomes from a metaphase cell followed by direct resolution of the haplotype for each allele.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] In genetics, a **gametic phase** represents the original allelic combinations that a diploid individual inherits from both parents.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] It is therefore a particular association of alleles at different loci on the same chromosome.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Gametic phase is influenced by genetic linkage.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Unlike other chromosomes, Y chromosomes generally do not come in pairs.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Every human male (excepting those with XYY syndrome) has only one copy of that chromosome.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] This means that there is not any chance variation of which copy is inherited, and also (for most of the chromosome) not any shuffling between copies by recombination; so, unlike autosomal haplotypes, there is effectively not any randomisation of the Y-chromosome haplotype between generations.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] A human male should largely share the same Y chromosome as his father, give or take a few mutations; thus Y chromosomes tend to pass largely intact from father to son, with a small but accumulating number of mutations that can serve to differentiate male lineages.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] In particular, the Y-DNA represented as the numbered results of a Y-DNA genealogical DNA test should match, except for mutations.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Unique-event polymorphisms (UEPs) such as SNPs represent haplogroups.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The results that comprise the full Y-DNA haplotype from the Y chromosome DNA test can be divided into two parts: the results for UEPs, sometimes loosely called the SNP results as most UEPs are single-nucleotide polymorphisms, and the results for microsatellite short tandem repeat sequences (Y-STRs).
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The UEP results represent the inheritance of events it is believed can be assumed to have happened only once in all human history.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] These can be used to identify the individual's Y-DNA haplogroup, his place in the "family tree" of the whole of humanity.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Genetic results also include the **Y-STR haplotype**, the set of results from the Y-STR markers tested.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Unlike the UEPs, the Y-STRs mutate much more easily, which allows them to be used to distinguish recent genealogy.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] But it also means that, rather than the population of descendants of a genetic event all sharing the *same* result, the Y-STR haplotypes are likely to have spread apart, to form a *cluster* of more or less similar results.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Typically, this cluster will have a definite most probable center, the **modal haplotype** (presumably similar to the haplotype of the original founding event), and also a **haplotype diversity** — the degree to which it has become spread out.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The further in the past the defining event occurred, and the more that subsequent population growth occurred early, the greater the haplotype diversity will be for a particular number of descendants.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] However, if the haplotype diversity is smaller for a particular number of descendants, this may indicate a more recent common ancestor, or a recent population expansion.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Unlike for UEPs, two individuals with a similar Y-STR haplotype may not necessarily share a similar ancestry.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Instead, the clusters of Y-STR haplotype results inherited from different events and different histories tend to overlap.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] In most cases, it is a long time since the haplogroups' defining events, so typically the cluster of Y-STR haplotype results associated with descendants of that event has become rather broad.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] These results will tend to significantly overlap the (similarly broad) clusters of Y-STR haplotypes associated with other haplogroups.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] This makes it impossible for researchers to predict with absolute certainty to which Y-DNA haplogroup a Y-STR haplotype would point.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] If the UEPs are not tested, the Y-STRs may be used only to predict probabilities for haplogroup ancestry, but not certainties.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] A similar scenario exists in trying to evaluate whether shared surnames indicate shared genetic ancestry.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] A cluster of similar Y-STR haplotypes may indicate a shared common ancestor, with an identifiable modal haplotype, but only if the cluster is sufficiently distinct from what may have happened by chance from different individuals who historically adopted the same name independently.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Many names were adopted from common occupations, for instance, or were associated with habitation of particular sites.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] More extensive haplotype typing is needed to establish genetic genealogy.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Commercial DNA-testing companies now offer their customers testing of more numerous sets of markers to improve definition of their genetic ancestry.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The number of sets of markers tested has increased from 12 during the early years to 111 more recently.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Establishing plausible relatedness between different surnames data-mined from a database is significantly more difficult.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The researcher must establish that the *very nearest* member of the population in question, chosen purposely from the population for that reason, would be unlikely to match by accident.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] This is more than establishing that a *randomly selected* member of the population is unlikely to have such a close match by accident.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Because of the difficulty, establishing relatedness between different surnames as in such a scenario is likely to be impossible, except in special cases where there is specific information to drastically limit the size of the population of candidates under consideration.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Haplotype diversity is a measure of the uniqueness of a particular haplotype in a given population.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The haplotype diversity (H) is computed as: $H={\frac {N}{N-1}}(1-\sum _{i}x_{i}^{2})$ where $x_{i}$ is the (relative) haplotype frequency of each haplotype in the sample and N is the sample size.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] Haplotype diversity is given for each sample.
[src:genome-wide-association/haplotype] The term "haplotype" was first introduced by MHC biologist Ruggero Ceppellini during the Third International Histocompatibility Workshop to substitute "pheno-group".
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] In defining LD, it is important first to distinguish two different concepts: linkage disequilibrium and linkage (genetic linkage).
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Linkage disequilibrium refers to the association of genes *in a population.* Linkage, on the other hand, tells us whether genes are on the same chromosome *in an individual*.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] There is no necessary relationship between the two.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Genes that are closely linked may or may not be associated in populations.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Looking at parents and offspring, if genes at closely linked loci are present together in the parent, then they will usually be found together in the offspring.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] But looking at individuals in a population with no known common ancestry, it is much more difficult to see any relationships.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] To give a concrete, although imaginary, example in terms of frequencies of characters, consider a case where the "gene for red hair" is closely linked to the "gene for blue eyes".
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] What does that tell us about the expected population frequency of individuals with red hair and blue eyes?
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Are all redheads expected to have blue eyes, just because the genes controlling these characters are closely linked?
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Consider an allele *A* at the *A* locus with frequency *pA* in a particular population.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] At a linked *B* locus, the frequency of the allele *B* is *pB*.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The question is, what is the expected frequency *pAB* of the allele pair, or *haplotype*, *AB*?
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] If the *A* and *B* alleles are independent in a population, then, by definition, *pAB* is simply the product *p*A*pB*.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Departure of *D* from zero indicates LD.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The descriptors "allele *A* at the *A* locus" and "allele *B* at the *B* locus" seem unnecessarily complicated.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Why not just the "*A* gene" and the "*B* gene"?
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The problem is that the term "gene" has been used since the foundation of genetics without a clear understanding of what a gene actually is.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] So, despite its widespread popular usage, its use is now avoided in genetics journals (see for a discussion about the changing definition of the gene).
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This is unfortunate for discussions of population frequencies where the nature of the gene is not important.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Use of the term "allele" rather than "gene" sidesteps this problem, but in a way that is not entirely satisfactory.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Allele was originally defined and still understood as meaning "alternative", and allele *A* and allele *B* are not alleles (of each other).
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The easiest way of talking about these linked "things" would be to use the term "gene".
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The expectation, dating back to 1918, is that LD is NOT to be expected, even for loci that are closely linked.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Robbins showed that recombination is expected to decrease the value of *D* in each generation by a factor (1 - *c*), where *c* is the frequency of recombination.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] If there is some recombination, *c* will be greater than zero, *Dt* approaches zero as *t* becomes large.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] For the example given previously, no association is expected between hair colour and eye colour.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The frequency of individuals who are both red-headed and blue-eyed is expected to become simply the product of the frequency of red-headed individuals multiplied by the frequency of blue-eyed individuals, despite the fact that the two characters are controlled by closely linked loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Selection provides one possible way in which LD might be expected, in spite of the above argument.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] If particular gene combinations are favoured, selection can cause LD to arise in the population, maintaining the frequency of the favoured gene combinations.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Such "equilibrium models" require reasonably high levels of selection, specifically "selective interaction", which is only possible for a minority of gene pairs.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The term LD remains as a legacy from this period.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] It was introduced for cases where there is known recombination but where the population has not come to equilibrium for the gene pair in question.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] But the most prominent uses of LD now involve very closely linked DNA bases (see below).
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Independence cannot be expected in such cases.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The 'disequilibrium' description seems inappropriate, with its implication that this situation is temporary and/or unexpected.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The molecular era for population genetics can be said to date from 1966 following the studies of Lewontin and Hubby in Drosophila and Harris in humans.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Using protein electrophoresis, these authors showed that around one third of loci must be 'polymorphic', having some genetic differences between individuals in the population.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Given the large number of loci in the genome and the limited amount of recombination, it followed that there must be many very closely linked polymorphic loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Subsequent DNA sequencing, e.g. the International HapMap Project has shown that protein studies considerably underestimate the amount of polymorphism.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] There will usually be thousands of genetic differences, titled Single Nucleotide Polymorphism or SNPs, within short regions of the genome.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Cases of zero or very low recombination must be common.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] A second important finding pertaining to LD was the realisation that LD can arise simply because of population structure.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Studies such as those of Robbins referred to above essentially assume an infinite population size.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Small population size, in particular, can lead to LD quite independently of any selection.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] It became clear that LD, rather than being rare and of secondary importance, must be widespread.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This has had enormous importance in diverse fields of human genetics and animal breeding.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] It means that any gene of importance is likely to be surrounded by DNA SNPs in high LD with the gene of interest.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The position of the gene may be unknown, but the position of all DNA SNPs is known exactly.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This has allowed the mapping of causal genes in human genetics, using Genome-wide association studies (GWAS).
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] It has allowed DNA 'breeding values' to be used as predictors, leading to advances in animal and plant breeding.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Haplotype frequencies can be set out in the form of a table with **x** and **y** columns.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Allele *A* is given the value '1' and allele *a* the value '0' in the **x** column.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Gamete frequencies are of the form *gi*, summing to 1.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] which is equivalent to the LD coefficient, *D*, as defined above.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This LD measure was introduced by Sewall Wright and its use popularised by Hill and Robertson.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The above LD theory is based on haploid frequencies.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] In practice, direct observation of such frequencies is rarely possible, since in most species of interest only diploid genotypes can be observed.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Assumptions need to be made to infer haploid frequencies.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] A different approach to estimating LD from diploid frequencies is to calculate the covariance and correlation of frequencies, just as for haploid frequencies.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Gao et al show that the diploid covariance is the same as "Burrows' composite LD measure".
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The table below shows *x* and *y* values for diploid genotypes.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] It also shows the expected frequencies on the assumption of random mating.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Normalising by the variances, the factor 2 cancels out.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Surprisingly, this is identical to the haploid LD correlation *rAB*.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The result is, as mentioned above, an expectation based on the assumption of random mating.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] If the deviation from random mating is expressed in terms of the inbreeding coefficient *F*, the expected frequency of *AABB* homozygotes is equal to (1-*F*)*g*12 + *Fg*1, the expected frequency of non-homozygotes such as *AABb* is equal to (1-*F*)*g*1*g*2 etc.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] For two biallelic loci, where *a* and *b* are the other alleles at these two loci, the restrictions are so strong that only one value of *D* is sufficient to represent all linkage disequilibrium relationships between these alleles.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Their relationships can be characterized as follows.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The sign of *D* in this case is chosen arbitrarily.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The magnitude of *D* is more important than the sign of *D* because the magnitude of *D* is representative of the degree of linkage disequilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] However, positive *D* value means that the gamete is more frequent than expected while negative means that the combination of these two alleles are less frequent than expected.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Linkage disequilibrium in asexual populations can be defined in a similar way in terms of population allele frequencies.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Furthermore, it is also possible to define linkage disequilibrium among three or more alleles, however these higher-order associations are not commonly used in practice.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The linkage disequilibrium D reflects both changes in the intensity of the linkage correlation and changes in gene frequency.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This poses an issue when comparing linkage disequilibrium between alleles with differing frequencies.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Normalization of linkage disequilibrium allows these alleles to be compared more easily.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The value of $D'$ will be within the range $-1\leq D'\leq 1$ .
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] When $-1\leq D'<0$ , the alleles are found less often than expected.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] When $0<D'\leq 1$ , the alleles are found more often than expected.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Note that $|D'|$ may be used in place of $D'$ when measuring how close two alleles are to linkage equilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The value of $r^{2}$ will be within the range $0\leq r^{2}\leq 1$ .
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] When $r^{2}=0$ , there is no correlation between the pair.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] When $r^{2}=1$ , the correlation is either perfect positive or perfect negative according to the sign of r .
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Another alternative normalizes D by the product of two of the four allele frequencies when the two frequencies represent alleles from the same locus.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This allows comparison of asymmetry between a pair of loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This is often used in case-control studies where **B** is the locus containing a disease allele.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Similar to the d method, this alternative normalizes D by the product of two of the four allele frequencies when the two frequencies represent alleles from different loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The measures $r^{2}$ and $D'$ have limits to their ranges and do not range over all values of zero to one for all pairs of loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The maximum of $r^{2}$ depends on the allele frequencies at the two loci being compared and can only range fully from zero to one where either the allele frequencies at both loci are equal, $P_{A}=P_{B}$ where $D>0$ , or when the allele frequencies have the relationship $P_{A}=1-P_{B}$ when $D<0$ .
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] While $D'$ can always take a maximum value of 1, its minimum value for two loci is equal to $|r|$ for those loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Consider the haplotypes for two loci A and B with two alleles each—a two-loci, two-allele model.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Note that these are relative frequencies.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] If the two loci and the alleles are independent from each other, then we would expect the frequency of each haplotype to be equal to the product of the frequencies of its corresponding alleles (e.g. $x_{11}=p_{1}q_{1}$ ).
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Thus, if the loci were inherited independently, then $x_{11}=p_{1}q_{1}$ , so $D=0$ , and there is linkage equilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] However, if the observed frequency of haplotype $A_{1}B_{1}$ were higher than what would be expected based on the individual frequencies of $A_{1}$ and $B_{1}$ then $x_{11}>p_{1}q_{1}$ , so $D>0$ , and there is positive linkage disequilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Conversely, if the observed frequency were lower, then $x_{11}<p_{1}q_{1}$ , $D<0$ , and there is negative linkage disequilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The following table illustrates the relationship between the haplotype frequencies and allele frequencies and D.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Additionally, we can normalize our data based on what we are trying to accomplish.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] For example, if we aim to create an association map in a case-control study, then we may use the d method due to its asymmetry.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] If we are trying to find the probability that a given haplotype will descend in a population without being recombined by other haplotypes, then it may be better to use the ρ method.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] But for most scenarios, $r^{2}$ tends to be the most popular method due to the usefulness of the correlation coefficient in statistics.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] A couple examples of where $r^{2}$ may be very useful would include measuring the recombination rate in an evolving population, or detecting disease associations.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Using the notation above, $D=x_{11}-p_{1}q_{1}$ , we can demonstrate this convergence to zero as follows.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This follows because a fraction $(1-c)$ of the haplotypes in the offspring have not recombined, and are thus copies of a random haplotype in their parents.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] A fraction c have recombined these two loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] where D at the n -th generation is designated as $D_{n}$ .
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] If at some time we observe linkage disequilibrium, it will disappear in the future due to recombination.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] However, the smaller the distance between the two loci, the smaller will be the rate of convergence of D to zero.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Once linkage disequilibrium has been calculated for a dataset, a visualization method is often chosen to display the linkage disequilibrium to make it more easily understandable.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The most common method is to use a heatmap, where colors are used to indicate the loci with positive linkage disequilibrium, and linkage equilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This example displays the full heatmap, but because the heatmap is symmetrical across the diagonal (that is, the linkage disequilibrium between loci A and B is the same as between B and A), a triangular heatmap that shows the pairs only once is also commonly employed.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This method has the advantage of being easy to interpret, but it also cannot display information about other variables that may be of interest.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] More robust visualization options are also available, like the textile plot.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] In a textile plot, combinations of alleles at a certain loci can be linked with combinations of alleles at a different loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Each genotype (combination of alleles) is represented by a circle which has an area proportional to the frequency of that genotype, with a column for each loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Lines are drawn from each circle to the circles in the other column(s), and the thickness of the connecting line is proportional to the frequency that the two genotypes occur together.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Linkage disequilibrium is seen through the number of line crossings in the diagram, where a greater number of line crossings indicates a low linkage disequilibrium and fewer crossings indicate a high linkage disequilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Another visualization option is forests of hierarchical latent class models (FHLCM).
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] All loci are plotted along the top layer of the graph, and below this top layer, boxes representing latent variables are added with links to the top level.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] Lines connect the loci at the top level to the latent variables below, and the lower the level of the box that the loci are connected to, the greater the linkage disequilibrium and the smaller the distance between the loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] While this method does not have the same advantages of the textile plot, it does allow for the visualization of loci that are far apart without requiring the sequence to be rearranged, as is the case with the textile plot.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] This is not an exhaustive list of visualization methods, and multiple methods may be used to display a data set in order to give a better picture of the data based on the information that the researcher aims to highlight.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The International HapMap Project enables the study of LD in human populations online.
[src:genome-wide-association/linkage-disequilibrium] The Ensembl project integrates HapMap data with other genetic information from dbSNP.
[src:genome-wide-association/manhattan-plot] A **Manhattan plot** is a type of plot, usually used to display data with a large number of data-points, many of non-zero amplitude, and with a distribution of higher-magnitude values.
[src:genome-wide-association/manhattan-plot] The plot is commonly used in genome-wide association studies (GWAS) to display significant SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/manhattan-plot] It gains its name from the similarity of such a plot to the Manhattan skyline: a profile of skyscrapers towering above the lower level "buildings" which vary around a lower height.
[src:genome-wide-association/manhattan-plot] In GWAS Manhattan plots, genomic coordinates are displayed along the *x*-axis, with the negative logarithm of the association *p*-value for each single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) displayed on the *y*-axis, meaning that each dot on the Manhattan plot signifies an SNP.
[src:genome-wide-association/manhattan-plot] Because the strongest associations have the smallest *p*-values (e.g., 10−15), their negative logarithms will be the greatest (e.g., 15).
[src:genome-wide-association/manhattan-plot] The different colors of each block usually show the extent of each chromosome.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In genetics, a **polygenic score** (**PGS**) is a number that summarizes the estimated effect of many genetic variants on an individual's phenotype.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The PGS is also called the **polygenic index** (**PGI**) or **genome-wide score**; in the context of disease risk, it is called a **polygenic risk score** (**PRS** or **PR score**) or **genetic risk score**.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The score reflects an individual's estimated genetic predisposition for a given trait and can be used as a predictor for that trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] It gives an estimate of how likely an individual is to have a given trait based only on genetics, without taking environmental factors into account; and it is typically calculated as a weighted sum of trait-associated alleles.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Recent progress in genetics has developed polygenic predictors of complex human traits, including risk for many important complex diseases that are typically affected by many genetic variants, each of which confers a small effect on overall risk.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In a polygenic risk predictor, the lifetime (or age-range) risk for the disease is a numerical function captured by the score which depends on the states of thousands of individual genetic variants (i.e., single-nucleotide polymorphisms, or SNPs).
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Polygenic scores are widely used in animal breeding and plant breeding due to their efficacy in improving livestock breeding and crops.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In humans, polygenic scores are typically generated from data of genome-wide association study (GWAS).
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] They are an active area of research spanning topics such as learning algorithms for genomic prediction; new predictor training; validation testing of predictors; and clinical application of PRS.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In 2018, the American Heart Association named polygenic risk scores as one of the major breakthroughs in research in heart disease and stroke.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] DNA in living organisms is the molecular genetic code for life.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Although polygenic risk scores from studies in humans have gained the most attention, the basic idea was first introduced for selective plant and animal breeding.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Similar to the latter-day approaches of constructing a polygenic risk score, an individual's—animal or plant—breeding value was calculated to be the combined weight of several single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) by their individual effects on a trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Human DNA contains about 3 billion bases.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The human genome can be broadly separated into coding and non-coding sequences, where the coding genome encodes instructions for genes, including some of the sequence that codes for proteins.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Genome-wide association studies (GWASes) enable mapping phenotypes to the variations in nucleotide bases in human populations.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Improvements in methodology and studies with large cohorts have enabled mapping many traits—some of which are diseases—to the human genome.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Learning which variations influence which specific traits and how strongly they do so is the key target for constructing polygenic scores in humans.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The methods were first considered for humans after the year 2000, and specifically by a 2007 proposal that such scores could be used in human genetics to identify individuals at high risk for disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The concept was successfully applied in 2009 by researchers who organized a genome-wide association study regarding schizophrenia with the objective of constructing scores of risk propensity.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] That study was the first to use the term *polygenic score* for a prediction drawn from a linear combination of single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) genotypes—which was able to explain 3% of the variance in schizophrenia.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] A PRS is constructed from the estimated effect sizes derived from a genome-wide association study (GWAS).
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In a GWAS, single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) are tested for an association between *cases* and *controls* (see graphic above).
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The results from a GWAS estimate the strength of the association at each SNP (i.e., the effect size at the SNP) as well as a p-value for statistical significance.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] A typical score is then calculated by adding the number of risk-modifying alleles across a large number of SNPs, whereby the number of alleles for each SNP is multiplied by the weight for the given SNP.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] This idea can be generalized to the study of any trait and is an example of the more general mathematical term regression analysis.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Methods for generating polygenic scores in humans are an active area of research.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Two key considerations in developing polygenic scores are *which* SNPs and the *number* of SNPs to include.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The simplest method—the so-called "pruning and thresholding" method—sets weights equal to the coefficient estimates from a regression of the trait on each genetic variant.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The included SNPs may be selected using an algorithm that attempts to ensure that each marker is approximately independent.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The independence of each SNP is important for the score's predictive accuracy.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] SNPs that are physically close to each other are more likely to be in linkage disequilibrium, meaning they typically are inherited together and therefore do not provide independent predictive power.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The removal of these SNPs is called "pruning".
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The "thresholding" refers to using only SNPs that meet a specific p-value threshold.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Penalized regression can also be used to construct polygenic scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] From prior information, penalized regression assigns probabilities based on: 1) how many genetic variants are expected to affect a trait and 2) the distribution of their effect sizes.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] These methods, in effect, "penalize" the large coefficients in a regression model and shrink them conservatively.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] One popular tool for this approach is "PRS-CS".
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Another is to use Bayesian methods, first proposed in 2001, that directly incorporate genetic features of a given trait and genomic features like linkage disequilibrium.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] One Bayesian method uses "linkage disequilibrium prediction" or LDpred.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] More approaches for developing polygenic risk scores continue to be described.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For example, by incorporating effect sizes from populations of different ancestral backgrounds, the predictive ability of scores can be improved.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Incorporating knowledge of the functional roles of specific genomic chunks can improve the utility of scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Studies have examined the performances of these methods on standardized dataset.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] As the number of genome-wide association studies has exploded, along with rapid advances in methods for calculating polygenic scores, its most obvious application is in clinical settings for disease prediction or risk stratification.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] It is important not to over- or under-state the value of polygenic scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] A key advantage of quantifying polygenic contribution for each individual is that the genetic liability does not change over an individual's lifespan.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] However, while a disease may have strong genetic contributions, the risk arising from one's genetics has to be interpreted in the context of environmental factors.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For example, even if an individual has a high genetic risk for alcoholism, that risk is lessened if that individual is never exposed to alcohol.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For humans, while most polygenic scores are not predictive enough to diagnose disease, they could be used in addition to other covariates (such as age, BMI, smoking status) to improve estimates of disease susceptibility.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] However, even if a polygenic score might not make reliable diagnostic predictions across an entire population, it may still make very accurate predictions for outliers at extreme high or low risk.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The clinical utility may therefore still be large even if average measures of prediction performance are moderate.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Other researchers recognize that polygenic under-prediction in non-European population should galvanize new GWAS that prioritize greater genetic diversity in order to maximize the potential health benefits brought about by predictive polygenic scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Significant scientific efforts are being made to this end.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Embryo genetic screening is common with millions biopsied and tested each year worldwide.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Genotyping methods have been developed so that the embryo genotype can be determined to high precision.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Testing for aneuploidy and monogenetic diseases has increasingly become established over decades, whereas tests for polygenic diseases have begun to be employed more recently, having been first used in embryo selection in 2019.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The use of polygenic scores for embryo selection has been criticised due to alleged ethical and safety issues as well as limited practical utility.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] However, trait-specific evaluations claiming the contrary have been put forth and ethical arguments for PGS-based embryo selection have also been made.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The topic continues to be an active area of research not only within genomics but also within clinical applications and ethics.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] As of 2019, polygenic scores from well over a hundred phenotypes have been developed from genome-wide association statistics.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] These include scores that can be categorized as anthropometric, behavioural, cardiovascular, non-cancer illness, psychiatric/neurological, and response to treatment/medication.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] When predicting disease risk, a PGS gives a continuous score that estimates the risk of having or getting the disease, within some pre-defined time span.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] A common metric for evaluating such continuous estimates of yes/no questions (see Binary classification) is the area under the ROC curve (AUC).
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The performance of a polygenic predictor is highly dependent on the size of the dataset that is available for analysis and ML training.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Recent scientific progress in prediction power relies heavily on the creation and expansion of large biobanks containing data for both genotypes and phenotypes of very many individuals.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] As of 2021, there exist several biobanks with hundreds of thousands samples, i.e., data entries with both genetic and trait information for each individual (see for instance the incomplete list of biobanks).
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] With the use of these growing biobanks, data from many thousands of individuals are used to detect the relevant variants for a specific trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Exactly how many are required depends very much on the trait in question.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Typically, increasing levels of prediction are observed until a plateau phase where the performance levels off and does not change much when increasing the sample size even further.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] This is the limit of how accurate a polygenic predictor that only uses genetic information can be and is set by the heritability of the specific trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The sample size required to reach this performance level for a certain trait is determined by the complexity of the underlying genetic architecture and the distribution of genetic variance in the sampled population.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] This sample size dependence is illustrated in the figure for hypothyroidism, hypertension and type 2 diabetes.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Note again, that current methods to construct polygenic predictors are sensitive to the ancestries present in the data.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] As of 2021, most available data have been primarily of populations with European ancestry, which is the reason why PGS generally perform better within this ancestry.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The construction of more diverse biobanks with successful recruitment from all ancestries is required to rectify this skewed access to and benefits from PGS-based medicine.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] A landmark study examining the role of polygenic risk scores in cardiovascular disease invigorated interest the clinical potential of polygenic scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] This study demonstrated that an individual with the highest polygenic risk score (top 1%) had a lifetime cardiovascular risk >10% which was comparable to those with rare genetic variants.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] This comparison is important because clinical practice can be influenced by knowing which individuals have this rare genetic cause of cardiovascular disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Since this study, polygenic risk scores have shown promise for disease prediction across other traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Polygenic risk scores have been studied heavily in obesity, coronary artery disease, diabetes, breast cancer, prostate cancer, Alzheimer's disease and psychiatric diseases.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] As of January 2021 providing PRS directly to individuals was undergoing research trials in health systems around the world, but is not yet offered as standard of care.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Most use is therefore through consumer genetic testing, where a number of private companies report PRS for a number of diseases and traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Consumers download their genotype (genetic variant) data and upload them into online PRS calculators, e.g.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Scripps Health, Impute.me or Color Genomics.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The most frequently reported motivation for individuals to seek out PRS reports is general curiosity (98.2%), and the reactions are generally mixed with common misinterpretations.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] It is speculated that personal use of PRS could contribute to treatment choices, but that more data is needed.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] As of 2020 a more typical use was that clinicians face individuals with commercially derived disease-specific PRS in the expectation that the clinician will interpret them, something that may create extra burdens for the clinical care system.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] At a fundamental level, the use of polygenic scores in clinical context will have similar technical issues as existing tools.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For example, if a tool is not validated in a diverse population, then it may exacerbate disparities with unequal efficacy across populations.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] This is especially important in genetics where, as of 2018, a majority of the studies to date have been done in Europeans.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Other challenges that can arise include how precisely the polygenic risk score can be calculated and how precise it needs to be for clinical utility.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Even if a polygenic score is accurately calculated and calibrated for a population, its interpretation must be approached with caution.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] First, it is important to realize that polygenic traits are different from monogenic traits; the latter stem from fewer genetic loci and can be detected more accurately.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Genetic tests are often difficult to interpret and require genetic counseling.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Currently, polygenic-score results are being shared with clinicians.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Since monogenic genetic testing is far more mature than polygenic scores, we can look there for approximating the clinical impact of polygenic scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] While some studies have found negative effects of returning monogenic genetic results to patients, the majority of studies have that negative consequences are minor.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Unlike many other clinical laboratory or imaging methods, an individual's germ-line genetic risk can be calculated at birth for a variety of diseases after sequencing their DNA once.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Thus, polygenic scores may ultimately be a cost-effective measure that can be informative for clinical management.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Moreover, the polygenic risk score may be informative across an individual's lifespan helping to quantify the genetic lifelong risk for certain diseases.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For many diseases, having a strong genetic risk can results in an earlier onset of presentation (e.g.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Recognizing an increased genetic burden earlier can allow clinicians to intervene earlier and avoid delayed diagnoses.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Polygenic score can be combined with traditional risk factors to increase clinical utility.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For example, polygenic risk scores may help improve diagnosis of diseases.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] This is especially evident in distinguishing Type 1 from Type 2 Diabetes.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Likewise, a polygenic risk score based approach may reduce invasive diagnostic procedures as demonstrated in Celiac disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Polygenic scores may also empower individuals to alter their lifestyles to reduce risk for diseases.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] While there is some evidence for behavior modification as a result of knowing one's genetic predisposition, more work is required to evaluate risk-modifying behaviors across a variety of different disease states.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Population level screening is another use case for polygenic scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The goal of population-level screening is to identify patients at high risk for a disease who would benefit from an existing treatment.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Polygenic scores can identify a subset of the population at high risk that could benefit from screening.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Several clinical studies are being done in breast cancer and heart disease is another area that could benefit from a polygenic score based screening program.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] A variety of applications exists for polygenic scores.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In humans, polygenic scores were originally computed in an effort to predict the prevalence and etiology of complex, heritable diseases, which are typically affected by many genetic variants that individually confer a small effect to overall risk.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Polygenic scores also have useful statistical properties in (genomic) association testing, for instance to account for outcome-specific background effects and/or improve statistical power.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The benefit of polygenic scores is that they can be used to predict the future for crops, animal breeding, and humans alike.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Although the same basic concepts underlie these areas of prediction, they face different challenges that require different methodologies.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] The ability to produce very large family size in nonhuman species, accompanied by deliberate selection, leads to a smaller effective population, higher degrees of linkage disequilibrium among individuals, and a higher average genetic relatedness among individuals within a population.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For example, members of plant and animal breeds that humans have effectively created, such as modern maize or domestic cattle, are all technically "related".
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In human genomic prediction, by contrast, unrelated individuals in large populations are selected to estimate the effects of common SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In both cases, however, sample size is key for maximizing the accuracy of genomic prediction.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] While modern genomic prediction scoring in humans is generally referred to as a "polygenic score" (PGS) or a "polygenic risk score" (PRS), in livestock the more common term is "genomic estimated breeding value", or GEBV (similar to the more familiar "EBV", but with genotypic data).
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Conceptually, a GEBV is the same as a PGS: a linear function of genetic variants that are each weighted by the apparent effect of the variant.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] Despite this, polygenic prediction in livestock is useful for a fundamentally different reason than for humans.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In humans, a PRS is used for the prediction of individual phenotype, while in livestock a GEBV is typically used to predict the offspring's average value of a phenotype of interest in terms of the genetic material it inherited from a parent.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] In this way, a GEBV can be understood as the average of the offspring of an individual or pair of individual animals.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] GEBVs are also typically communicated in the units of the trait of interest.
[src:genome-wide-association/polygenic-score] For example, the expected increase in milk production of the offspring of a specific parent compared to the offspring from a reference population might be a typical way of using a GEBV in dairy cow breeding and selection.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] A **quantitative trait locus** (**QTL**) is a locus (section of DNA) that correlates with variation of a quantitative trait in the phenotype of a population of organisms.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] QTLs are mapped by identifying which molecular markers (such as SNPs or AFLPs) correlate with an observed trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This is often an early step in identifying the actual genes that cause the trait variation.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] A **quantitative trait locus** (**QTL**) is a region of DNA which is associated with a particular phenotypic trait, which varies in degree and which can be attributed to polygenic effects, i.e., the product of two or more genes, and their environment.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] These QTLs are often found on different chromosomes.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The number of QTLs which explain variation in the phenotypic trait indicates the genetic architecture of a trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] It may indicate that plant height is controlled by many genes of small effect, or by a few genes of large effect.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Typically, QTLs underlie continuous traits (those traits which vary continuously, e.g. height) as opposed to discrete traits (traits that have two or several character values, e.g. red hair in humans, a recessive trait, or smooth vs. wrinkled peas used by Mendel in his experiments).
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Moreover, a single phenotypic trait is usually determined by many genes.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Consequently, many QTLs are associated with a single trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Another use of QTLs is to identify candidate genes underlying a trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The DNA sequence of any genes in this region can then be compared to a database of DNA for genes whose function is already known, this task being fundamental for marker-assisted crop improvement.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Mendelian inheritance was rediscovered at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] As Mendel's ideas spread, geneticists began to connect Mendel's rules of inheritance of single factors to Darwinian evolution.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] For early geneticists, it was not immediately clear that the smooth variation in traits like body size (i.e., incomplete dominance) was caused by the inheritance of single genetic factors.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] An early attempt by William Ernest Castle to unify the laws of Mendelian inheritance with Darwin's theory of speciation invoked the idea that species become distinct from one another as one species or the other acquires a novel Mendelian factor.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Darwin discussed the inheritance of similar mutant features but did not invoke them as a requirement of speciation.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Instead Darwin used the emergence of such features in breeding populations as evidence that mutation can occur at random within breeding populations, which is a central premise of his model of selection in nature.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Later in his career, Castle would refine his model for speciation to allow for small variation to contribute to speciation over time.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] He also was able to demonstrate this point by selectively breeding laboratory populations of rats to obtain a hooded phenotype over several generations.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Castle's work was among the first to attempt to unify the recently rediscovered laws of Mendelian inheritance with Darwin's theory of evolution.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Still, it would be almost thirty years until the theoretical framework for evolution of complex traits would be widely formalized.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Quantitative trait genetics today leverages Wright's observations about the statistical relationship between genotype and phenotype in families and populations to understand how certain genetic features can affect variation in natural and derived populations.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] An example of a polygenic trait is human skin color variation.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Several genes factor into determining a person's natural skin color, so modifying only one of those genes can change skin color slightly or in some cases, such as for SLC24A5, moderately.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Many disorders with genetic components are polygenic, including autism, cancer, diabetes and numerous others.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Most phenotypic characteristics are the result of the interaction of multiple genes.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Multifactorially inherited diseases are said to constitute the majority of genetic disorders affecting humans which will result in hospitalization or special care of some kind.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Traits controlled both by the environment and by genetic factors are called multifactorial.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Usually, multifactorial traits outside of illness result in what we see as **continuous characteristics** in organisms, especially human organisms such as: height, skin color, and body mass.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] All of these phenotypes are complicated by a great deal of give-and-take between genes and environmental effects.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The continuous distribution of traits such as height and skin color described above, reflects the action of genes that do not manifest typical patterns of dominance and recessiveness.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Instead the contributions of each involved locus are thought to be additive.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Writers have distinguished this kind of inheritance as *polygenic*, or *quantitative inheritance*.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Thus, due to the nature of polygenic traits, inheritance will not follow the same pattern as a simple monohybrid or dihybrid cross.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Polygenic inheritance can be explained as Mendelian inheritance at many loci, resulting in a trait which is normally-distributed.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] If *n* is the number of involved loci, then the coefficients of the binomial expansion of (*a* + *b*)*2n* will give the frequency of distribution of all *n* allele combinations.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] For sufficiently high values of *n*, this binomial distribution will begin to resemble a normal distribution.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] From this viewpoint, a disease state will become apparent at one of the tails of the distribution, past some threshold value.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Disease states of increasing severity will be expected the further one goes past the threshold and away from the mean.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] A mutation resulting in a disease state is often recessive, so both alleles must be mutant in order for the disease to be expressed phenotypically.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] A disease or syndrome may also be the result of the expression of mutant alleles at more than one locus.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] When more than one gene is involved, with or without the presence of environmental triggers, we say that the disease is the result of multifactorial inheritance.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The more genes involved in the cross, the more the distribution of the genotypes will resemble a normal, or Gaussian distribution.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This shows that multifactorial inheritance is polygenic, and genetic frequencies can be predicted by way of a polyhybrid Mendelian cross.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Phenotypic frequencies are a different matter, especially if they are complicated by environmental factors.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The paradigm of polygenic inheritance as being used to define multifactorial disease has encountered much disagreement.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Turnpenny (2004) discusses how simple polygenic inheritance cannot explain some diseases such as the onset of Type I diabetes mellitus, and that in cases such as these, not all genes are thought to make an equal contribution.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The assumption of polygenic inheritance is that all involved loci make an equal contribution to the symptoms of the disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This should result in a normal (Gaussian) distribution of genotypes.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] When it does not, the idea of polygenetic inheritance cannot be supported for that illness.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The above are well-known examples of diseases having both genetic and environmental components.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Other examples involve atopic diseases such as eczema or dermatitis, spina bifida (open spine), and anencephaly (open skull).
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] While schizophrenia is widely believed to be multifactorially genetic by biopsychiatrists, no characteristic genetic markers have been determined with any certainty.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] If it is shown that the brothers and sisters of the patient have the disease, then there is a strong chance that the disease is genetic and that the patient will also be a genetic carrier.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This is not quite enough as it also needs to be proven that the pattern of inheritance is non-Mendelian.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This would require studying dozens, even hundreds of different family pedigrees before a conclusion of multifactorial inheritance is drawn.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] If multifactorial inheritance is indeed the case, then the chance of the patient contracting the disease is reduced only if cousins and more distant relatives have the disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] While multifactorially-inherited diseases tend to run in families, inheritance will not follow the same pattern as a simple monohybrid or dihybrid cross.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] If a genetic cause is suspected and little else is known about the illness, then it remains to be seen exactly how many genes are involved in the phenotypic expression of the disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Once that is determined, the question must be answered: if two people have the required genes, why are there differences in expression between them?
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Generally, what makes the two individuals different are likely to be environmental factors.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Due to the involved nature of genetic investigations needed to determine such inheritance patterns, this is not usually the first avenue of investigation one would choose to determine etiology.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] For organisms whose genomes are known, one might now try to exclude genes in the identified region whose function is known with some certainty not to be connected with the trait in question.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] If the genome is not available, it may be an option to sequence the identified region and determine the putative functions of genes by their similarity to genes with known function, usually in other genomes.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This can be done using BLAST, an online tool that allows users to enter a primary sequence and search for similar sequences within the BLAST database of genes from various organisms.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Another interest of statistical geneticists using QTL mapping is to determine the complexity of the genetic architecture underlying a phenotypic trait.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] For example, they may be interested in knowing whether a phenotype is shaped by many independent loci, or by a few loci, and do those loci interact.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This can provide information on how the phenotype may be evolving.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] In a recent development, classical QTL analyses were combined with gene expression profiling i.e. by DNA microarrays.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Such expression QTLs (eQTLs) describe cis- and trans-controlling elements for the expression of often disease-associated genes.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Observed epistatic effects have been found beneficial to identify the gene responsible by a cross-validation of genes within the interacting loci with metabolic pathway- and scientific literature databases.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The simplest method for QTL mapping is analysis of variance (ANOVA, sometimes called "marker regression") at the marker loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] In this method, in a backcross, one may calculate a t-statistic to compare the averages of the two marker genotype groups.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] For other types of crosses (such as the intercross), where there are more than two possible genotypes, one uses a more general form of ANOVA, which provides a so-called F-statistic.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The ANOVA approach for QTL mapping has three important weaknesses.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] First, we do not receive separate estimates of QTL location and QTL effect.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] QTL location is indicated only by looking at which markers give the greatest differences between genotype group averages, and the apparent QTL effect at a marker will be smaller than the true QTL effect as a result of recombination between the marker and the QTL.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Second, we must discard individuals whose genotypes are missing at the marker.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Third, when the markers are widely spaced, the QTL may be quite far from all markers, and so the power for QTL detection will decrease.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Lander and Botstein developed interval mapping, which overcomes the three disadvantages of analysis of variance at marker loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Interval mapping is currently the most popular approach for QTL mapping in experimental crosses.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The method makes use of a genetic map of the typed markers, and, like analysis of variance, assumes the presence of a single QTL.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] In interval mapping, each locus is considered one at a time and the logarithm of the odds ratio (LOD score) is calculated for the model that the given locus is a true QTL.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The odds ratio is related to the Pearson correlation coefficient between the phenotype and the marker genotype for each individual in the experimental cross.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The term 'interval mapping' is used for estimating the position of a QTL within two markers (often indicated as 'marker-bracket').
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Interval mapping is originally based on the maximum likelihood but there are also very good approximations possible with simple regression.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The principle for QTL mapping is: 1) The likelihood can be calculated for a given set of parameters (particularly QTL effect and QTL position) given the observed data on phenotypes and marker genotypes.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] 2) The estimates for the parameters are those where the likelihood is highest.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] 3) A significance threshold can be established by permutation testing.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Conventional methods for the detection of quantitative trait loci (QTLs) are based on a comparison of single QTL models with a model assuming no QTL.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] For instance in the "interval mapping" method the likelihood for a single putative QTL is assessed at each location on the genome.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] However, QTLs located elsewhere on the genome can have an interfering effect.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] As a consequence, the power of detection may be compromised, and the estimates of locations and effects of QTLs may be biased (Lander and Botstein 1989; Knapp 1991).
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Even nonexisting so-called "ghost" QTLs may appear (Haley and Knott 1992; Martinez and Curnow 1992).
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Therefore, multiple QTLs could be mapped more efficiently and more accurately by using multiple QTL models.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] One popular approach to handle QTL mapping where multiple QTL contribute to a trait is to iteratively scan the genome and add known QTL to the regression model as QTLs are identified.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] This method, termed composite interval mapping determine both the location and effects size of QTL more accurately than single-QTL approaches, especially in small mapping populations where the effect of correlation between genotypes in the mapping population may be problematic.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] In this method, one performs interval mapping using a subset of marker loci as covariates.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] These markers serve as proxies for other QTLs to increase the resolution of interval mapping, by accounting for linked QTLs and reducing the residual variation.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The key problem with CIM concerns the choice of suitable marker loci to serve as covariates; once these have been chosen, CIM turns the model selection problem into a single-dimensional scan.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] The choice of marker covariates has not been solved, however.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Not surprisingly, the appropriate markers are those closest to the true QTLs, and so if one could find these, the QTL mapping problem would be complete anyway.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Inclusive composite interval mapping (ICIM) has also been proposed as a potential method for QTL mapping.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Family-based QTL mapping, or Family-pedigree based mapping (Linkage and association mapping), involves multiple families instead of a single family.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Family-based QTL mapping has been the only way for mapping of genes where experimental crosses are difficult to make.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] However, due to some advantages, now plant geneticists are attempting to incorporate some of the methods pioneered in human genetics.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Using family-pedigree based approach has been discussed (Bink et al.
[src:genome-wide-association/quantitative-trait-locus] Family-based linkage and association has been successfully implemented (Rosyara et al.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In genetics and bioinformatics, a **single-nucleotide polymorphism** (**SNP** /snɪp/; plural **SNPs** /snɪps/) is a germline substitution of a single nucleotide at a specific position in the genome.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Although certain definitions require the substitution to be present in a sufficiently large fraction of the population (e.g.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] 1% or more), many publications do not apply such a frequency threshold.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, a G nucleotide present at a specific location in a reference genome may be replaced by an A in a minority of individuals.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The two possible nucleotide variations of this SNP – G or A – are called alleles.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs can help explain differences in susceptibility to a wide range of diseases across a population.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, a common SNP in the CFH gene is associated with increased risk of age-related macular degeneration.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Differences in the severity of an illness or response to treatments may also be manifestations of genetic variations caused by SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, two common SNPs in the *APOE* gene, rs429358 and rs7412, lead to three major APO-E alleles with different associated risks for development of Alzheimer's disease and age at onset of the disease.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single nucleotide substitutions with an allele frequency of less than 1% are sometimes called single-nucleotide variants.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] "Variant" may also be used as a general term for any single nucleotide change in a DNA sequence, encompassing both common SNPs and rare mutations, whether germline or somatic.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The term single-nucleotide variant has therefore been used to refer to point mutations found in cancer cells.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] DNA variants must also commonly be taken into consideration in molecular diagnostics applications such as designing PCR primers to detect viruses, in which the viral RNA or DNA sample may contain single-nucleotide variants.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, this nomenclature uses arbitrary distinctions (such as an allele frequency of 1%) and is not used consistently across all fields; the resulting disagreement has prompted calls for a more consistent framework for naming differences in DNA sequences between two samples.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single-nucleotide polymorphisms may fall within coding sequences of genes, non-coding regions of genes, or in the intergenic regions (regions between genes).
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs within a coding sequence do not necessarily change the amino acid sequence of the protein that is produced, due to degeneracy of the genetic code.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs in the coding region are of two types: synonymous SNPs and nonsynonymous SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Synonymous SNPs do not affect the protein sequence, while nonsynonymous SNPs change the amino acid sequence of protein.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs that are not in protein-coding regions may still affect gene splicing, transcription factor binding, messenger RNA degradation, or the sequence of noncoding RNA.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Gene expression affected by this type of SNP is referred to as an eSNP (expression SNP) and may be upstream or downstream from the gene.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] More than 600 million SNPs have been identified across the human genome in the world's population.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] A typical genome differs from the reference human genome at 4–5 million sites, most of which (more than 99.9%) consist of SNPs and short indels.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The genomic distribution of SNPs is not homogenous; SNPs occur in non-coding regions more frequently than in coding regions or, in general, where natural selection is acting and "fixing" the allele (eliminating other variants) of the SNP that constitutes the most favorable genetic adaptation.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Other factors, like genetic recombination and mutation rate, can also determine SNP density.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNP density can be predicted by the presence of microsatellites: AT microsatellites in particular are potent predictors of SNP density, with long (AT)(n) repeat tracts tending to be found in regions of significantly reduced SNP density and low GC content.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since there are variations between human populations, a SNP allele that is common in one geographical or ethnic group may be rarer in another.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, this pattern of variation is relatively rare; in a global sample of 67.3 million SNPs, the Human Genome Diversity Project "found no such private variants that are fixed in a given continent or major region.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The highest frequencies are reached by a few tens of variants present at >70% (and a few thousands at >50%) in Africa, the Americas, and Oceania.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Within a population, SNPs can be assigned a minor allele frequency (MAF)—the lowest allele frequency at a locus that is observed in a particular population.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This is simply the lesser of the two allele frequencies for single-nucleotide polymorphisms.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With this knowledge, scientists have developed new methods in analyzing population structures in less studied species.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] By using pooling techniques, the cost of the analysis is significantly lowered.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These techniques are based on sequencing a population in a pooled sample instead of sequencing every individual within the population by itself.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With new bioinformatics tools, there is a possibility of investigating population structure, gene flow, and gene migration by observing the allele frequencies within the entire population.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With these protocols there is a possibility for combining the advantages of SNPs with micro satellite markers.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, there is information lost in the process, such as linkage disequilibrium and zygosity information.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single nucleotide polymorphisms serve as powerful molecular markers in contemporary genetic research and clinical practice.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Association studies, particularly genome-wide association studies (GWAS), represent the primary application of SNP technology for identifying genetic variants linked to human diseases and traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The development of tag SNP methodology has significantly enhanced the efficiency of genomic studies by exploiting patterns of linkage disequilibrium across the human genome.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Tag SNPs function as representative markers that capture genetic variation within specific chromosomal regions, allowing researchers to survey large genomic areas without genotyping every individual variant.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This approach reduces both the financial cost and computational burden of large-scale genetic studies while maintaining sufficient power to detect disease-associated loci.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The selection of optimal tag SNPs relies on sophisticated algorithms that identify markers capable of capturing the maximum amount of genetic information within defined genomic intervals.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Haplotype reconstruction represents another fundamental application where SNPs enable the characterization of inherited genetic blocks.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Researchers utilize dense SNP maps to identify and analyze haplotype structures, which consist of sets of closely linked alleles that tend to be transmitted together through generations.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These haplotype patterns provide insights into population history, demographic events, and evolutionary processes that have shaped contemporary genetic diversity.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The International HapMap Project exemplified this application by creating comprehensive maps of common haplotype patterns across diverse human populations.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Linkage disequilibrium analysis forms the theoretical foundation for many SNP-based applications in population genetics and disease mapping.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This phenomenon describes the non-random association of alleles at different genomic positions, which occurs when variants are inherited together more frequently than would be expected by chance alone.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The extent of linkage disequilibrium between SNPs depends primarily on physical distance along chromosomes and local recombination rates, with closer variants generally showing stronger associations.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Understanding these patterns enables researchers to predict which SNPs will provide redundant information and guides the selection of informative markers for association studies.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In genetic epidemiology, SNPs have emerged as essential tools for investigating disease transmission patterns and population structure.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Whole-genome sequencing approaches utilize SNP variation to define transmission clusters in infectious disease outbreaks, where cases showing similar genetic profiles may represent linked transmission events.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This application has proven particularly valuable for tuberculosis surveillance and contact tracing, where traditional epidemiological methods may fail to identify all transmission links.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Additionally, SNP-based analyses contribute to understanding population stratification and ancestry, which are crucial factors in designing appropriate study controls and interpreting association results across diverse ethnic groups.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Variations in the DNA sequences of humans can affect how humans develop diseases and respond to pathogens, chemicals, drugs, vaccines, and other agents.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs are also critical for personalized medicine.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Examples include biomedical research, forensics, pharmacogenetics, and disease causation, as outlined below.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] One of the main contributions of SNPs in clinical research is genome-wide association study (GWAS).
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide genetic data can be generated by multiple technologies, including SNP array and whole genome sequencing.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] GWAS has been commonly used in identifying SNPs associated with diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since GWAS is a genome-wide assessment, a large sample site is required to obtain sufficient statistical power to detect all possible associations.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some SNPs have relatively small effect on diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] To estimate study power, the genetic model for disease needs to be considered, such as dominant, recessive, or additive effects.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Due to genetic heterogeneity, GWAS analysis must be adjusted for race.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association study is commonly used in genetic study before the invention of high throughput genotyping or sequencing technologies.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association study is to investigate limited number of pre-specified SNPs for association with diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] So this is a hypothesis driven approach.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since only a limited number of SNPs are tested, a relatively small sample size is sufficient to detect the association.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association approach is also commonly used to confirm findings from GWAS in independent samples.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide SNP data can be used for homozygosity mapping.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Homozygosity mapping is a method used to identify homozygous autosomal recessive loci, which can be a powerful tool to map genomic regions or genes that are involved in disease pathogenesis.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Recently, preliminary results reported SNPs as important components of the epigenetic program in organisms.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Moreover, cosmopolitan studies in European and South Asiatic populations have revealed the influence of SNPs in the methylation of specific CpG sites.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In addition, meQTL enrichment analysis using GWAS database, demonstrated that those associations are important toward the prediction of biological traits.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs have historically been used to match a forensic DNA sample to a suspect but has been made obsolete due to advancing STR-based DNA fingerprinting techniques.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, the development of next-generation-sequencing (NGS) technology may allow for more opportunities for the use of SNPs in phenotypic clues such as ethnicity, hair color, and eye color with a good probability of a match.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This can additionally be applied to increase the accuracy of facial reconstructions by providing information that may otherwise be unknown, and this information can be used to help identify suspects even without a STR DNA profile match.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some cons to using SNPs versus STRs is that SNPs yield less information than STRs, and therefore more SNPs are needed for analysis before a profile of a suspect is able to be created.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Additionally, SNPs heavily rely on the presence of a database for comparative analysis of samples.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, in instances with degraded or small volume samples, SNP techniques are an excellent alternative to STR methods.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs (as opposed to STRs) have an abundance of potential markers, can be fully automated, and a possible reduction of required fragment length to less than 100 bp.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Pharmacogenetics focuses on identifying genetic variations including SNPs associated with differential responses to treatment.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Many drug metabolizing enzymes, drug targets, or target pathways can be influenced by SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The SNPs involved in drug metabolizing enzyme activities can change drug pharmacokinetics, while the SNPs involved in drug target or its pathway can change drug pharmacodynamics.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Therefore, SNPs are potential genetic markers that can be used to predict drug exposure or effectiveness of the treatment.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide pharmacogenetic study is called pharmacogenomics.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Pharmacogenetics and pharmacogenomics are important in the development of precision medicine, especially for life-threatening diseases such as cancers.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Only small amount of SNPs in the human genome may have impact on human diseases.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Large scale GWAS has been done for the most important human diseases, including heart diseases, metabolic diseases, autoimmune diseases, and neurodegenerative and psychiatric disorders.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Most of the SNPs with relatively large effects on these diseases have been identified.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These findings have significantly improved understanding of disease pathogenesis and molecular pathways, and facilitated development of better treatment.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Further GWAS with larger samples size will reveal the SNPs with relatively small effect on diseases.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For common and complex diseases, such as type-2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis, and Alzheimer's disease, multiple genetic factors are involved in disease etiology.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In addition, gene-gene interaction and gene-environment interaction also play an important role in disease initiation and progression.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] As there are for genes, bioinformatics databases exist for SNPs.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The International SNP Map working group mapped the sequence flanking each SNP by alignment to the genomic sequence of large-insert clones in Genebank.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These alignments were converted to chromosomal coordinates that is shown in Table 1.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This list has greatly increased since, with, for instance, the Kaviar database now listing 162 million single nucleotide variants.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The nomenclature for SNPs include several variations for an individual SNP, while lacking a common consensus.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The rs### standard is that which has been adopted by dbSNP and uses the prefix "rs", for "reference SNP", followed by a unique and arbitrary number.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs are frequently referred to by their dbSNP rs number, as in the examples above.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The Human Genome Variation Society (HGVS) uses a standard which conveys more information about the SNP.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The first section is usually a chromosome or mRNA identifier, such as NC_000023.10 (DNA) or NM_004006.3 (mRNA).
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The type of change is denoted by a string.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs can be easily assayed due to only containing two possible alleles and three possible genotypes involving the two alleles: homozygous A, homozygous B and heterozygous AB, leading to many possible techniques for analysis.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some include: DNA sequencing; capillary electrophoresis; mass spectrometry; single-strand conformation polymorphism (SSCP); single base extension; electrochemical analysis; denaturating HPLC and gel electrophoresis; restriction fragment length polymorphism; and hybridization analysis.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] An important group of SNPs are those that corresponds to missense mutations causing amino acid change on protein level.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Point mutation of particular residue can have different effect on protein function (from no effect to complete disruption its function).
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Usually, change in amino acids with similar size and physico-chemical properties (e.g. substitution from leucine to valine) has mild effect, and opposite.
[src:genome-wide-association/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Similarly, if SNP disrupts secondary structure elements (e.g. substitution to proline in alpha helix region) such mutation usually may affect whole protein structure and function.
